text:
SOIL SAMPLING AND GEOLOGICAL RECONNAISSANCE 
 The south west quarter of the tenement is occupied by out cropping granodiorite. 
 Detailed aeromagnetics suggests that mafic and ultramafic rocks outcropping in the 
 SE part of the tenement extend under cover in contact with granite through to the NW 
 corner.  Broad spaced soil sampling of ferruginous gravels, reworked laterite and duri 
 crust expressed elevated Ni, Cu, Cr, Au values which tend to support this.  Sufficient 
 anomalous soil results were generated to warrant future RAB or aircore drilling to test 
 Previously, 182, -2mm soil samples on a 500m x 500m offset grid were taken over 
 most of the tenement plus selected short soil traverses (50m intervals) over specific 
 interpreted  aeromagnetic  targets.  Follow-up  of  anomalous  results  gained  from  this 
 program was done during the reporting period comprising 310 soil samples on a 100 x 
 400m grid (31 line km) plus general geological field reconnaissance.  These results 
 are not currently available and a supplementary report will be submitted as soon as the 
 A shallow drilling program planned for the period to follow up this sampling had to 
 be abandoned due to the presence of a registered sacred site on the tenement (location 
 unknown) which precludes any mechanical ground disturbance being undertaken until 
 the completion of a detailed anthropological field study on behalf of the traditional 
 owners (Wangatha) which is in progress at the time of compiling this report.
